Good question. One hacky way of detecting TCO could be to cause a stack overflow:<p><pre><code>  var supportsTco = false;
  try {
    (function rec(n) { if(n) rec(n - 1) })(20000);
    supportsTco = true;
  } 
  catch (e) { /* Ignore stack overflow error */ }
</code></pre>
This works for me on Firefox and Chrome (by &quot;works&quot; i mean it doesn&#x27;t, because no browser implements TCO yet, but the code detects it). But it&#x27;s not bullet-proof: it would fail on a JS runtime with no TCO but a higher stack size limit, or on a runtime that detects this specific case of recursion and optimizes into a loop (or completely eliminates the innocuous function call).<p>A side-question: does anybody else feel that stack overflows just don&#x27;t belong in high level languages? I mean, most high level languages remove the distinction between stack-allocated values and heap-allocated ones: it&#x27;s all references. It doesn&#x27;t make sense to worry about whether a Ruby (or JS, or Python, etc) object lives on the heap or on the stack. But yet, you still have to worry about the function call stack on these languages, and they all have tiny limits (in the order of the thousands stack frames) compared to the heap size limit.<p>Wouldn&#x27;t it be possible for a language to make the stack grow without an arbitrary limit (besides the limit of physical memory)? And if so, why do these high level languages that focus on ease of use not implement the stack that way?
